{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 10:07:22.615589", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of current network health\\n- Layer-3 connectivity across user subnets and the server farm is healthy. Pings between hosts and server subnet endpoints show 0% loss and low latency.\\n- Web services (Apache backends and the Nginx load balancer) are reachable over HTTP by IP address and are listening on TCP/80.\\n- Name resolution is not functioning for the local zone from user hosts; HTTP requests by hostname time out.\\n\\nKey anomalies detected\\n1) DNS service outage on dns_server (10.200.0.2)\\n- Symptom: From both hosts, HTTP requests to hostnames (e.g., http://web99.local, http://web0.local) consistently take ~5 seconds and do not connect, indicating resolver timeout. In contrast, the same services by IP complete quickly (~1–2 seconds).\\n- Symptom: getent hosts web99.local/web0.local on hosts times out.\\n- Test: dig @10.200.0.2 web0.local and dig @10.200.0.2 web99.local from host_1_1_1_1 both time out; no servers could be reached.\\n- Test: On dns_server, dig to both 127.0.0.1 and 10.200.0.2 also times out (no responding DNS service even locally).\\n- Service state: bind9 on dns_server is inactive (dead) per systemctl; indicates the authoritative/resolver process is not running.\\n- Note: netstat on dns_server shows numerous TCP/UDP 53 listeners, but no responses are observed to any dig queries; given systemctl status and repeated timeouts, the effective DNS process is not serving queries.\\n\\n2) Application-plane access by IP is normal\\n- host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 can curl 10.200.0.7 (load balancer) and 10.200.0.3 (web_server_0); total times ~1–2 seconds with normal connect and TTFB.\\n- All web servers (web_server_0..3) and the load balancer report TCP/80 listening.\\n\\n3) Routing/transport plane appears healthy\\n- ICMP reachability:\\n  - Hosts to DNS (10.200.0.2), DHCP (10.200.0.8), load balancer (10.200.0.7), and web servers (10.200.0.3–.6) all succeed with 0% loss and low RTTs (typically 2–5 ms).\\n  - Cross-host ping (host_1_1_1_1 ↔ host_2_1_1_1) succeeds with low RTT.\\n- This indicates OSPF routing between user subnets and the server farm is functioning and there are no apparent ACL/forwarding issues for IP transport.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- Faulty device: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- Fault domain: Application/service layer on dns_server (Bind9 DNS service).\\n- Not a network forwarding or routing problem: ICMP to dns_server succeeds from hosts and servers; TCP/UDP toward other services are working; the failure is isolated to DNS service responsiveness.\\n\\nRoot cause assessment\\n- Root cause: DNS daemon (bind9) is not running (inactive/dead). With DNS unreachable, all hostname resolutions (e.g., web0.local, web99.local) from clients fail, causing HTTP-by-name attempts to hang and time out, while direct connections by IP continue to work.\\n\\nRelevant evidence excerpts\\n- From hosts:\\n  - curl http://web99.local and http://web0.local: namelookup/connect/pretransfer all 0; total ≈ 5.0 s per attempt, consistent with resolver timeout.\\n  - curl http://10.200.0.7 and http://10.200.0.3: normal connect and starttransfer; total ≈ 1.0–2.1 s.\\n  - dig @10.200.0.2 web0.local: timed out; no servers could be reached.\\n  - resolv.conf on both hosts: nameserver 10.200.0.2; nsswitch hosts: files dns.\\n- On dns_server:\\n  - systemctl status bind9: Active: inactive (dead).\\n  - dig @127.0.0.1 localhost and dig @10.200.0.2 localhost: both time out, confirming DNS service nonresponsive even locally.\\n\\nNon-issues (validated as healthy)\\n- IP reachability between all critical endpoints (hosts, load balancer, web servers, DHCP server) is normal with low latency and 0% loss.\\n- HTTP services on web servers and the load balancer are listening and reachable by IP.\\n- OSPF/routing across core/dist/server segments appears operational from data-plane results.\\n\\nImpact\\n- End-user service by hostname is degraded/unavailable due to DNS failure; services remain reachable by IP, but normal user workflows relying on names (web0.local…web3.local and web99.local) will fail or experience long delays., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='97f09e1f-56ab-4285-8791-3f12d951af26'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
